      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used in the analysis (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) is commercially validated; version control and audit trail documented in the simulation plan. Required Gradation 2 for Model Risk Level 3.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is an FDA-recognized simulation software platform. A simulation plan with documented version, license number, and analyst qualifications was maintained throughout the study. Independent verification of input files performed by a second analyst. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and Ansys verification manual executed; results within 1% of analytical solutions for beam bending and contact pressure benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark problems (linear beam bending, Hertzian contact, large-displacement column) executed in the study configuration. Maximum deviation from analytical solution was 0.7%. Code verification requirement satisfied at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change < 2% between medium and fine mesh; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities evaluated (coarse: 42k elements, medium: 118k elements, fine: 310k elements). QoI change between medium and fine meshes was 1.3% for stiffness and 1.8% for yield force. Richardson extrapolation yielded a discretization uncertainty of 0.9% on stiffness. Medium mesh selected for production runs. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Default solver tolerances documented; energy and force residuals reported for each simulation run.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver used with default force and displacement convergence tolerances (0.5% and 1.0% respectively). Residual histories archived for all 11 simulation runs. No convergence failures observed. Gradation 1 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation plan reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions and loading consistent with ASTM F1717 protocol as documented.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and contact pair definitions against the simulation plan prior to production runs. Three discrepancies identified and corrected during review. Final model reviewed and signed off. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Bilinear isotropic hardening constitutive model selected based on published Ti-6Al-4V tensile data; model form justified relative to loading regime and failure mode.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO) model with published Ti-6Al-4V material constants (E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, E_T=2.2 GPa) selected. Justification documented: loading is quasi-static, strain rates are low, and the dominant failure mode is plastic bending of the screw shank. Sensitivity to tangent modulus evaluated; QoI variation < 3% over plausible range. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for the specific screw lot; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of representative screws.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E, sigma_y, E_T) obtained from certified material test reports for the Ti-6Al-4V screw lot used in bench testing. Geometric dimensions verified against CMM measurements of three representative screws from the test lot; deviations from nominal < 0.05 mm. Input uncertainty propagated via one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from a single production lot; lot traceability documented; dimensional inspection of test articles confirms conformance to drawing.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs assembled from a single production lot of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws. Lot traceability documented. CMM inspection of three randomly selected screws confirmed dimensional conformance. UHMWPE blocks from the same lot used across both laboratories. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two distinct test configurations (e.g., varying offset distance or block material) evaluated to demonstrate robustness of model predictions.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively at the standard ASTM F1717 offset distance (50 mm) and at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min). Only one UHMWPE block hardness grade was used. The required Gradation 3 calls for at least two distinct test configurations to bracket clinical variability; only one configuration was evaluated. Gradation 2 achieved, falling short of the required Gradation 3. This gap was noted in the assessment but the overall decision was carried by the aggregate performance of the remaining twelve factors."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to those of the physical test articles; traceability table provided.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table maps each FEA input to its physical test counterpart with source documentation. Geometric inputs derived from CMM data; material inputs from certified test reports; boundary conditions replicate ASTM F1717 fixture constraints. No unresolved equivalency gaps identified. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation metric E/uval computed for each QoI; all values < 1.96 (95% confidence threshold); percentage difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result < 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed for stiffness (0.87), yield force (1.12), and force at 40 mm displacement (1.04); all below the 1.96 threshold. Mean percentage differences: stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 5.1%. All within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the same quantities used in the regulatory submission and directly linked to the clinical failure mode of interest.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are identical to those specified in the regulatory submission and in ASTM F1717. Stiffness characterises immediate post-operative stability; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement characterise fatigue-relevant structural margins. Direct linkage to clinical risk of screw fracture documented in the risk analysis. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions; any extrapolation from validation domain to COU is bounded and justified.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities use the identical screw geometry, UHMWPE block material, and ASTM F1717 loading protocol as specified in the COU. No extrapolation beyond the validated configuration is claimed. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU domain for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm design. Gradation 2 achieved."
    }
